{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Attention-based pooling, learned query resamplers (e.g., Q-Former/Perceiver-style), strided subsampling, and CTC-based temporal compression are all used to control the rate of audio tokens fed to the LLM, balancing information retention and compute.",
    "It is worth noting that several recent studies have explored novel alignment paradigms.",
    "For example, LegoSLM [84] leverages LLM word embeddings to construct weighted representations of speech signals, while AlignFormer [99] effectively simplifies speech feature sequences by operating directly on the CTC posterior distributions.",
    "In a similar spirit, TASU [100] further exploits CTC posteriors to more effectively extract semantic information from audio and to balance the information rate between the speech and text modalities.",
    "C. LLM InferenceThe LLM inference stage consists mainly of a text decoder, which is typically an autoregressive transformer decoder that generates text tokens conditioned on input audio and/or text."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For example, LegoSLM [84] leverages LLM word embeddings to construct weighted representations of speech signals, while AlignFormer [99] effectively simplifies speech feature sequences by operating directly on the CTC posterior distributions.",
